Demographic Exploration and Discovery: Color in R

Tim Riffe

June 26, 2019

Color

Basics on specification

You can always use named colors in once-off applications, but its hard to remember many names. In general, R ends up specifying colors in hex format, following the pattern "#RRGGBBAA", where # starts the string, RR is the red channel, GG is the green channel, BB is the blue channel, and AA is the alpha (transparency) channel. 00 is the lowest value, and FF is the highest, and 80 is 50%. Theres no point trying to figure out more than that unless youre really into hex. You just need to know that this is the transfer system that R uses.

In class we looked at an example of importing colors from an ad hoc online tool to R. That was colorgorical: http://vrl.cs.brown.edu/color

There are many many more, too many. Heres a fab blog post on color choices from Lisa Charlotte Rost: https://blog.datawrapper.de/colorguide/ and I highly encourage you to dig deeper.

However, some basic tools in R can pretty much give you everything you need to do a good job.

Ramps and palettes

Lets talk about sequential, diverging, and qualitative colors

library(colorspace)
hcl_palettes(plot = TRUE)

You can use these palettes like so (using ramp functions) to produce a vector of colors:

If you just want to do a test run to see how the colors perform in different standard plot types, feed your color vector to demoplot()

se <- sequential_hcl(10,"BurgYl")
demoplot(se,"map")

demoplot(se,"heatmap")

demoplot(se,"bar")

demoplot(se,"line")

demoplot(se,"scatter")

Or in the ggplot2 framework:

library("ggplot2")
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, fill = Species)) + 
    geom_density(alpha = 0.6) + 
    scale_fill_discrete_qualitative(palette = "Dark 2")

dsamp <- diamonds[1 + 1:1000 * 50, ]
ggplot(dsamp, aes(carat, price, color = cut)) + geom_point() +
  scale_color_discrete_sequential(palette = "Purples 3", nmax = 6, order = 2:6)

You can compose the different scale_color_ functions using the same pattern. Remember to compose these functions you build them using a tree diagram following this pattern:

  1. scale_
  2. color_ or fill_
  3. discrete_ or continuous_
  4. qualitative(), sequential(), or divergent()

For example, above we used scale_color_discrete_sequential().

And at a minimum you give palette = "blabla", where you get the palette name from that lookup table we referred to earlier. This just adds into the ggplot() statement that youre building.

Discrete vs continuous color

Only matters (probably) for Lexis surfaces, heatmaps, and maps in general. Continuous colors are interpolated through your data as-is, where the min and max are mapped to the min and max of the given palette, and the color path goes through the control points that make up the given palette. If your surface is smooth, youll see that, but it can be very hard to pick out trends in a smooth surface. Discrete colors reveal trends, but these may depend on the actual value intervals used to bin colors.

Check out Jonas Schleys HMD explorer to remember the effect that continuous versus discrete colors can have on a map: https://jschoeley.shinyapps.io/hmdexp/

Background vs foreground

Control plot noise and focus your message by using the notion of plot foreground and background. The background is best if it gives perspective, a comparison group for whom the constituent parts are less important, but desaturated so as to be not distracting. Your main finding around which you want to build a message then goes in the foreground- brighter, bolder, more saturated. Heres an example using a bunch of life expectancies from HMD:

library(tidyverse)
##  Attaching packages  tidyverse 1.2.1 
##  tibble  2.1.1        purrr   0.3.2  
##  tidyr   0.8.3        dplyr   0.8.0.1
##  readr   1.3.1        stringr 1.4.0  
##  tibble  2.1.1        forcats 0.4.0
##  Conflicts  tidyverse_conflicts() 
##  dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
##  dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
library(HMDHFDplus)
countries <- getHMDcountries()
HMDe0 <- list()
for (i in countries){
      HMDe0[[i]] <- readHMDweb(CNTRY = i,
                 item = "E0per", 
                 username = us, # remember not to save charcacter
                 password = pw) # strings of passwords in scripts!
}

HMDe0 <- bind_rows(HMDe0, .id = "Country")

p <- ggplot(HMDe0, mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Male))
p + geom_line(aes(group = Country), alpha = .3, color = gray(.5)) + 
    xlim(1950,2017) + 
    ylim(50,85) + 
    geom_line(data=subset(HMDe0, Country == "USA"), color = "red",
              size = 2) + 
    annotate(geom = "text", 
             label = "post Soviet\nmortality crisis",
             x = 1990,
             y = 60)
## Warning: Removed 1789 rows containing missing values (geom_path).
## Warning: Removed 17 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

Lexis surfaces

Here are three geoms that might be useful for building Lexis surfaces. Remember, a Lexis surface is just an age by year Cartesian grid filled with some value. Usually we look at (log) rates, but it could be anything.

# grab Swedish deaths
DX <-readHMDweb(CNTRY = "SWE",
                item = "Deaths_1x1",
                username = us, 
                password = pw)

# Lexis structured data, but not on a Lexis surface:
p <- ggplot(DX, mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Male, fill = Age)) 
    p + geom_col() + 
        scale_fill_continuous_sequential(palette = "BurgYl") 

# using geom_tile() with contours
p <- ggplot(DX, mapping = aes(x=Year, y=Age, fill = log(Male)))
p + geom_tile() +
    scale_fill_continuous_sequential(palette = "BurgYl") + 
    geom_contour(mapping=aes(z=log(Male)), col = "black") + 
    coord_fixed()
## Warning: Removed 2283 rows containing non-finite values (stat_contour).

# and again using an underlying raster.
p + geom_raster() + coord_fixed()

Adding in coord_fixed makes the age units equal to the year units in space, which gives you an aspect ratio of 1, which is good practice for Lexis plots of all kinds.
